[src:play-framework/play-framework] Support for the Scala programming language has been available since version 1.1 of the framework.
[src:play-framework/play-framework] In version 2.0, the framework core was rewritten in Scala.
[src:play-framework/play-framework] Build and deployment was migrated to SBT, and templates use Scala instead of Apache Groovy.
[src:play-framework/play-framework] Play was created by software developer Guillaume Bort, while working at Zengularity SA (formerly Zenexity).
[src:play-framework/play-framework] Although the early releases are no longer available online, there is evidence of Play existing as far back as May 2007.
[src:play-framework/play-framework] In 2007, pre-release versions of the project were available to download from Zenexity's website.
[src:play-framework/play-framework] Play is heavily inspired by ASP.NET MVC, Ruby on Rails and Django and is similar to this family of frameworks.
[src:play-framework/play-framework] Play web applications can be written in Scala or Java, in an environment that may be less Java Enterprise Edition-centric.
[src:play-framework/play-framework] This can make Play simpler to develop compared to other Java-centric platforms.
[src:play-framework/play-framework] Although Play 1.x could also be packaged as WAR files to be distributed to standard Java EE application servers, Play 2.x applications are now designed to be run using the built-in Akka HTTP or Netty web servers exclusively.
[src:play-framework/play-framework] Play provides integration with test frameworks for unit testing and functional testing for both Scala and Java applications.
[src:play-framework/play-framework] For Scala, integrations with Scalatest and Specs2 are provided out-of-the-box and, for Java, there is integration with JUnit 4.
[src:play-framework/play-framework] For both languages, there is also integration with Selenium (software).
[src:play-framework/play-framework] SBT is used to run the tests and also to generate reports.
[src:play-framework/play-framework] It is also possible to use code coverage tools by using sbt plugins such as scoverage or jacoco4sbt.
[src:play-framework/play-framework] In August 2011, Heroku announced native support for Play applications on its cloud computing platform.
[src:play-framework/play-framework] This followed module-based support for Play 1.0 on Google App Engine, and documented support on Amazon Web Services.
[src:play-framework/play-framework] As of October 2013, the Play Framework was the most popular Scala project on GitHub.
[src:play-framework/play-framework] In July 2015, Play was the 3rd most popular Scala library in GitHub, based on 64,562 Libraries.
[src:play-framework/play-framework] 21.3% of the top Scala projects used Play as their framework of choice.
[src:play-framework/play-framework] Corporate users of the Play Framework have included Coursera, HuffPost, Hootsuite, Janrain, LinkedIn, and Connectifier.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] In computing, **reactive programming** is a declarative programming paradigm concerned with data streams and the propagation of change.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] With this paradigm, it is possible to express static (e.g., arrays) or dynamic (e.g., event emitters) data streams with ease, and also communicate that an inferred dependency within the associated execution model exists, which facilitates the automatic propagation of the changed data flow.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] For example, in *imperative* programming, `a := b + c` would mean that `a` is being assigned the result of `b + c` at the time the expression is evaluated, and later, the values of `b` and `c` can be changed with no effect on the value of `a`.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] In contrast, in *reactive* programming, the value of `a` is automatically updated whenever the values of `b` or `c` change, without the program having to explicitly re-state the statement `a := b + c` to re-assign the value of `a`.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] Another example is a hardware description language such as Verilog, where reactive programming enables changes to be modeled as they propagate through circuits.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] Reactive programming has been proposed as a way to simplify creating interactive user interfaces and near-real-time computing animation.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] For example, in a model–view–controller (MVC) architecture, reactive programming can facilitate changes in an underlying *model* being reflected automatically in an associated *view*.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] Several popular approaches are employed in creating reactive programming languages.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] One approach is the specification of *dedicated* languages that are specific to various *domain constraints*.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] Such constraints usually are characterized by real-time, embedded computing or hardware description.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] Another approach involves the specification of *general-purpose* languages that include support for reactivity.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] Other approaches are articulated in the definition, and use of programming *libraries*, or *embedded domain-specific languages*, that enable reactivity alongside or atop a programming language.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] Specification and use of these different approaches results in language *capability trade-offs*.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] In general, the more restricted a language is, the more its associated compilers and analysis programming tools are able to inform developers (e.g., in performing analysis for whether programs are able to execute in actual real-time).
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] Functional trade-offs in specificity may result in deterioration of the general applicability of a language.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] A variety of models and semantics govern reactive programming.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] Reactive programming language runtimes are represented by a graph that identifies the dependencies among the involved reactive values.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] In such a graph, *nodes* represent the act of computing, and *edges* model dependency relationships.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] Such a runtime employs said graph, to help it keep track of the various computations, which must be executed anew, once an involved input changes value.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] At the implementation level, *event reaction* consists of the propagation across a graph's information, which characterizes the existence of change.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] Consequently, computations that are affected by such change then become outdated and must be flagged for re-execution.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] Such computations are then usually characterized by the transitive closure of the change (i.e., the full set of transitive dependencies a source affects) in its associated source.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] *Change propagation* may then lead to an update in the value of the graph's *sinks*.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] Graph propagated information can consist of a node's complete state, i.e., the computation result of the involved node.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] In such cases, the node's previous output is then ignored.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] Another method involves *delta propagation* i.e.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] In this case, information is proliferated along a graph's *edges,* which consist only of *delta*s describing how the previous node was changed.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] This approach is especially important when *nodes* hold large amounts of *state data*, which would otherwise be expensive to recompute from scratch.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] Another common optimization is employment of *unary change accumulation* and *batch propagation*.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] Such a solution can be faster because it reduces communication among involved nodes.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] Optimization strategies can then be employed that reason about the nature of the changes contained within, and make alterations accordingly (e.g. two changes in the batch can cancel each other, and thus, simply be ignored).
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] Yet another available approach, is described as *invalidity notification propagation*.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] This approach causes nodes with invalid input to pull updates, thus resulting in the update of their own outputs.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] A graph of dependencies is program-specific and generated by a programmer.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] When propagating changes, it is possible to pick propagation orders such that the value of an expression is not a natural consequence of the source program.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] We can illustrate this easily with an example.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] Suppose `seconds` is a reactive value that changes every second to represent the current time (in seconds).
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] Because `t` should always be greater than `seconds`, this expression should always evaluate to a true value.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] Unfortunately, this can depend on the order of evaluation.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] When `seconds` changes, two expressions have to update: `seconds + 1` and the conditional.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] If the first evaluates before the second, then this invariant will hold.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] If, however, the conditional updates first, using the old value of `t` and the new value of `seconds`, then the expression will evaluate to a false value.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] Some reactive languages are glitch-free and prove this property.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] This is usually achieved by topologically sorting expressions and updating values in topological order.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] This can, however, have performance implications, such as delaying the delivery of values (due to the order of propagation).
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] Topological sorting of dependencies depends on the dependency graph being a directed acyclic graph (DAG).
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] In practice, a program may define a dependency graph that has cycles.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] Usually, reactive programming languages expect such cycles to be "broken" by placing some element along a "back edge" to permit reactive updating to terminate.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] Typically, languages provide an operator like `delay` that is used by the update mechanism for this purpose, since a `delay` implies that what follows must be evaluated in the "next time step" (allowing the current evaluation to terminate).
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] Reactive languages typically assume that their expressions are purely functional.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] This allows an update mechanism to choose different orders in which to perform updates, and leave the specific order unspecified (thereby enabling optimizations).
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] When a reactive language is embedded in a programming language with state, however, it may be possible for programmers to perform mutable operations.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] How to make this interaction smooth remains an open problem.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] In some cases, it is possible to have principled partial solutions.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] In some reactive languages, the graph of dependencies is *static*, i.e., the graph is fixed throughout a program's execution.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] In other languages, the graph can be *dynamic*, i.e., it can change as the program executes.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] Every second, the value of this expression changes to a different reactive expression, which `t + 1` then depends on.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] Therefore, the graph of dependencies updates every second.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] Permitting dynamic updating of dependencies provides significant expressive power (for instance, dynamic dependencies routinely occur in graphical user interface (GUI) programs).
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] However, the reactive update engine must decide whether to reconstruct expressions each time, or to keep an expression's node constructed but inactive; in the latter case, ensure that they do not participate in the computation when they are not supposed to be active.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] Reactive programming languages can range from very explicit ones where data flows are set up by using arrows, to implicit where the data flows are derived from language constructs that look similar to those of imperative or functional programming.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] For example, in an implicitly lifted functional reactive programming (FRP), a function call might implicitly cause a node in a data flow graph to be constructed.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] Reactive programming libraries for dynamic languages (such as the Lisp "Cells" and Python "Trellis" libraries) can construct a dependency graph from runtime analysis of the values read during a function's execution, allowing data flow specifications to be both implicit and dynamic.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] Sometimes the term *reactive programming* refers to the architectural level of software engineering, where individual nodes in the data flow graph are ordinary programs that communicate with each other.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] Reactive programming can be purely static where the data flows are set up statically, or be dynamic where the data flows can change during the execution of a program.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] The use of data switches in the data flow graph could to some extent make a static data flow graph appear as dynamic, and blur the distinction slightly.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] True dynamic reactive programming however could use imperative programming to reconstruct the data flow graph.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] Reactive programming could be said to be of **higher order** if it supports the idea that data flows could be used to construct other data flows.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] That is, the resulting value out of a data flow is another data flow graph that is executed using the same evaluation model as the first.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] Ideally all data changes are propagated instantly, but this cannot be assured in practice.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] Instead, it might be necessary to give different parts of the data flow graph different evaluation priorities.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] This can be called **differentiated reactive programming**.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] For example, in a word processor, marking spelling errors need not be synchronized fully with adding or inserting characters.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] Here, differentiated reactive programming can be used to give a spell checker lower priority, allowing it to be delayed while keeping other data flows more immediate.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] However, such differentiation introduces added design complexity.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] For example, deciding how to define the different data flow areas, and how to handle event passing between different data flow areas.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] Evaluation of reactive programs is not necessarily based on how stack-based programming languages are evaluated.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] Instead, when some data is changed, the change is propagated to all data that is derived partially or completely from the data that was changed.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] This change propagation could be achieved in a number of ways, where perhaps the most natural way is an invalidate/lazy-revalidate scheme.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] It could be problematic simply to naively propagate a change using a stack, because of potential exponential update complexity if the data structure has a certain shape.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] One such shape can be described as "repeated diamonds shape", and has the following structure: An→Bn→An+1, An→Cn→An+1, where n=1,2...
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] This problem could be overcome by propagating invalidation only when some data is not already invalidated, and later re-validate the data when needed using lazy evaluation.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] One inherent problem for reactive programming is that most computations that would be evaluated and forgotten in a normal programming language, needs to be represented in the memory as data-structures.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] This could potentially make reactive programming highly memory consuming.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] However, research on what is called *lowering* could potentially overcome this problem.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] On the other side, reactive programming is a form of what could be described as "explicit parallelism", and could therefore be beneficial for using the power of parallel hardware.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] Reactive programming has principal similarities with the observer pattern commonly used in object-oriented programming.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] However, integrating the data flow concepts into the programming language would make it easier to express them and could therefore increase the granularity of the data flow graph.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] For example, the observer pattern commonly describes data flows between whole objects/classes, whereas object-oriented reactive programming could target the members of objects/classes.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] It is possible to fuse reactive programming with ordinary imperative programming.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] In such a paradigm, imperative programs operate upon reactive data structures.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] Such a set-up is analogous to imperative constraint programming; however, while imperative constraint programming manages bidirectional data-flow constraints, imperative reactive programming manages one-way data-flow constraints.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] One reference implementation is the proposed Quantum runtime extension to JavaScript.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] Object-oriented reactive programming (OORP) is a combination of object-oriented programming and reactive programming.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] Perhaps the most natural way to make such a combination is this: instead of methods and fields, objects have *reactions* that automatically re-evaluate when the other reactions they depend on have been modified.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] If an OORP language maintains its imperative methods, it would also fall under the category of imperative reactive programming.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] Functional reactive programming (FRP) is a programming paradigm for reactive programming on functional programming.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] The actor model (actors) is proposed to design reactive systems, often combined with functional reactive programming (FRP) and Reactive Streams to develop distributed reactive systems.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] A newer category of programming languages uses constraints (rules) as main programming concept.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] It consists of reactions to events, which keep all constraints satisfied.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] Not only does this facilitate event-based reactions, but it makes reactive programs instrumental to the correctness of software.
[src:play-framework/reactive-programming] An example of a rule based reactive programming language is Ampersand, which is founded in relation algebra.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala source code can be compiled to JVM bytecode and run on a Java virtual machine (JVM).
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala can also be transpiled to JavaScript to run in a browser, or compiled directly to a native executable using Clang.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] When running on the JVM, Scala provides language interoperability with Java so that libraries written in either language may be referenced directly in Scala or Java code.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Like Java, Scala is object-oriented, and uses a syntax termed *curly-brace* which is similar to the language C.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Since Scala 3, there is also an option to use the off-side rule (indenting) to structure blocks, and its use is advised.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Martin Odersky has said that this turned out to be the most productive change introduced in Scala 3.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Unlike Java, Scala has many features of functional programming languages (like Scheme, Standard ML, and Haskell), including currying, immutability, lazy evaluation, and pattern matching.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] The name Scala is a portmanteau of *scalable* and *language*, signifying that it is designed to grow with the demands of its users.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] The design of Scala started in 2001 at the École Polytechnique Fédérale de Lausanne (EPFL) (in Lausanne, Switzerland) by Martin Odersky.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] It followed on from work on Funnel, a programming language combining ideas from functional programming and Petri nets.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Odersky formerly worked on Generic Java, and javac, Sun's Java compiler.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] After an internal release in late 2003, Scala was released publicly in early 2004 on the Java platform, A second version (v2.0) followed in March 2006.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] On 17 January 2011, the Scala team won a five-year research grant of over €2.3 million from the European Research Council.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] On 12 May 2011, Odersky and collaborators launched Typesafe Inc.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] (later renamed Lightbend Inc.), a company to provide commercial support, training, and services for Scala.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Typesafe received a $3 million investment in 2011 from Greylock Partners.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala runs on the Java platform (Java virtual machine) and is compatible with existing Java programs.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] The reference Scala software distribution, including compiler and libraries, is released under the Apache license.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala Native is a Scala compiler that targets the LLVM compiler infrastructure to create executable code that uses a lightweight managed runtime, which uses the Boehm garbage collector.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] The project is led by Denys Shabalin and had its first release, 0.1, on 14 March 2017.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Development of Scala Native began in 2015 with a goal of being faster than just-in-time compilation for the JVM by eliminating the initial runtime compilation of code and also providing the ability to call native routines directly.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] A reference Scala compiler targeting the .NET Framework and its Common Language Runtime was released in June 2004, but was officially dropped in 2012.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Unlike the stand-alone Hello World application for Java, there is no class declaration and nothing is declared to be static.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] This is analogous to the process for compiling and running Java code.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Indeed, Scala's compiling and executing model is identical to that of Java, making it compatible with Java build tools such as Apache Ant.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala includes an interactive shell and scripting support.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] The following example shows the differences between Java and Scala syntax.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] These syntactic relaxations are designed to allow support for domain-specific languages.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] The following example contrasts the definition of classes in Java and Scala.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala has the same compiling model as Java and C#, namely separate compiling and dynamic class loading, so that Scala code can call Java libraries.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala's operational characteristics are the same as Java's.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] The Scala compiler generates byte code that is nearly identical to that generated by the Java compiler.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] In fact, Scala code can be decompiled to readable Java code, with the exception of certain constructor operations.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] To the Java virtual machine (JVM), Scala code and Java code are indistinguishable.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] The only difference is one extra runtime library, `scala-library.jar`.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala adds a large number of features compared with Java, and has some fundamental differences in its underlying model of expressions and types, which make the language theoretically cleaner and eliminate several *corner cases* in Java.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] From the Scala perspective, this is practically important because several added features in Scala are also available in C#.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] As mentioned above, Scala has a good deal of syntactic flexibility, compared with Java.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] By themselves, these may seem like questionable choices, but collectively they serve the purpose of allowing domain-specific languages to be defined in Scala without needing to extend the compiler.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] For example, Erlang's special syntax for sending a message to an actor, i.e.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] `actor ! message` can be (and is) implemented in a Scala library without needing language extensions.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Java makes a sharp distinction between primitive types (e.g.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] `int` and `boolean`) and reference types (any class).
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Only reference types are part of the inheritance scheme, deriving from `java.lang.Object`.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] In Scala, all types inherit from a top-level class `Any`, whose immediate children are `AnyVal` (value types, such as `Int` and `Boolean`) and `AnyRef` (reference types, as in Java).
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] This means that the Java distinction between primitive types and boxed types (e.g.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] `Integer`) is not present in Scala; boxing and unboxing is completely transparent to the user.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala 2.10 allows for new value types to be defined by the user.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Instead of the Java "foreach" loops for looping through an iterator, Scala has `for`-expressions, which are similar to list comprehensions in languages such as Haskell, or a combination of list comprehensions and generator expressions in Python.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] For-expressions using the `yield` keyword allow a new collection to be generated by iterating over an existing one, returning a new collection of the same type.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] They are translated by the compiler into a series of `map`, `flatMap` and `filter` calls.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Where `yield` is not used, the code approximates to an imperative-style loop, by translating to `foreach`.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] (The expression `1 to 25` is not special syntax.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Expression `(mention, times) <- mentions` is an example of pattern matching (see below).
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Iterating over a map returns a set of key-value tuples, and pattern-matching allows the tuples to easily be destructured into separate variables for the key and value.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Similarly, the result of the comprehension also returns key-value tuples, which are automatically built back up into a map because the source object (from the variable `mentions`) is a map.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] If `mentions` instead held a list, set, array or other collection of tuples, exactly the same code above would yield a new collection of the same type.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] While supporting all of the object-oriented features available in Java (and in fact, augmenting them in various ways), Scala also provides a large number of capabilities that are normally found only in functional programming languages.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Together, these features allow Scala programs to be written in an almost completely functional style and also allow functional and object-oriented styles to be mixed.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Unlike C or Java, but similar to languages such as Lisp, Scala makes no distinction between statements and expressions.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] All statements are in fact expressions that evaluate to some value.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Functions that would be declared as returning `void` in C or Java, and statements like `while` that logically do not return a value, are in Scala considered to return the type `Unit`, which is a singleton type, with only one object of that type.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Functions and operators that never return at all (e.g. the `throw` operator or a function that always exits non-locally using an exception) logically have return type `Nothing`, a special type containing no objects; that is, a bottom type, i.e. a subclass of every possible type.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Similarly, an `if-then-else` "statement" is actually an expression, which produces a value, i.e. the result of evaluating one of the two branches.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] For similar reasons, `return` statements are unnecessary in Scala, and in fact are discouraged.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] As in Lisp, the last expression in a block of code is the value of that block of code, and if the block of code is the body of a function, it will be returned by the function.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Due to type inference, the type of variables, function return values, and many other expressions can typically be omitted, as the compiler can deduce it.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Examples are `val x = "foo"` (for an immutable constant or immutable object) or `var x = 1.5` (for a variable whose value can later be changed).
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Type inference in Scala is essentially local, in contrast to the more global Hindley-Milner algorithm used in Haskell, ML and other more purely functional languages.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] This is done to facilitate object-oriented programming.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] The result is that certain types still need to be declared (most notably, function parameters, and the return types of recursive functions), e.g.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] In Scala, functions are objects, and a convenient syntax exists for specifying anonymous functions.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] An example is the expression `x => x < 2`, which specifies a function with one parameter, that compares its argument to see if it is less than 2.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] It is equivalent to the Lisp form `(lambda (x) (< x 2))`.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Neither the type of x nor the return type need be explicitly specified, and can generally be inferred by type inference; but they can be explicitly specified, e.g., as `(x: Int) => x < 2` or even `(x: Int) => (x < 2): Boolean`.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Anonymous functions behave as true closures in that they automatically capture any variables that are lexically available in the environment of the enclosing function.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Those variables will be available even after the enclosing function returns, and unlike in the case of Java's *anonymous inner classes* do not need to be declared as final.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala enforces a distinction between immutable and mutable variables.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Mutable variables are declared using the `var` keyword and immutable values are declared using the `val` keyword.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] A variable declared using the `val` keyword cannot be reassigned in the same way that a variable declared using the `final` keyword can't be reassigned in Java.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] `val`s are only shallowly immutable, that is, an object referenced by a val is not guaranteed to itself be immutable.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Immutable classes are encouraged by convention however, and the Scala standard library provides a rich set of immutable collection classes.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala provides mutable and immutable variants of most collection classes, and the immutable version is always used unless the mutable version is explicitly imported.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] The immutable variants are persistent data structures that always return an updated copy of an old object instead of updating the old object destructively in place.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] An example of this is immutable linked lists where prepending an element to a list is done by returning a new list node consisting of the element and a reference to the list tail.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Appending an element to a list can only be done by prepending all elements in the old list to a new list with only the new element.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] In the same way, inserting an element in the middle of a list will copy the first half of the list, but keep a reference to the second half of the list.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] This allows for very easy concurrency — no locks are needed as no shared objects are ever modified.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Evaluation is strict ("eager") by default.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] In other words, Scala evaluates expressions as soon as they are available, rather than as needed.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] However, it is possible to declare a variable non-strict ("lazy") with the `lazy` keyword, meaning that the code to produce the variable's value will not be evaluated until the first time the variable is referenced.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Non-strict collections of various types also exist (such as the type `Stream`, a non-strict linked list), and any collection can be made non-strict with the `view` method.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Non-strict collections provide a good semantic fit to things like server-produced data, where the evaluation of the code to generate later elements of a list (that in turn triggers a request to a server, possibly located somewhere else on the web) only happens when the elements are actually needed.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Functional programming languages commonly provide tail call optimization to allow for extensive use of recursion without stack overflow problems.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Limitations in JVM bytecode complicate tail call optimization on the JVM.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] In general, a function that calls itself with a tail call can be optimized, but mutually recursive functions cannot.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Trampolines have been suggested as a workaround.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Trampoline support has been provided by the Scala library with the object `scala.util.control.TailCalls` since Scala 2.8.0 (released 14 July 2010).
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] A function may optionally be annotated with `@tailrec`, in which case it will not compile unless it is tail recursive.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] An example of this optimization could be implemented using the factorial definition.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] This ensures tail call optimization and thus prevents a stack overflow error.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala has built-in support for pattern matching, which can be thought of as a more sophisticated, extensible version of a switch statement, where arbitrary data types can be matched (rather than just simple types like integers, Booleans and strings), including arbitrary nesting.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] A special type of class known as a *case class* is provided, which includes automatic support for pattern matching and can be used to model the algebraic data types used in many functional programming languages.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] The idea here is that we partition a list into the elements less than a pivot and the elements not less, recursively sort each part, and paste the results together with the pivot in between.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] This uses the same divide-and-conquer strategy of mergesort and other fast sorting algorithms.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] The `match` operator is used to do pattern matching on the object stored in `list`.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Each `case` expression is tried in turn to see if it will match, and the first match determines the result.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] In this case, `Nil` only matches the literal object `Nil`, but `pivot :: tail` matches a non-empty list, and simultaneously *destructures* the list according to the pattern given.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] In this case, the associated code will have access to a local variable named `pivot` holding the head of the list, and another variable `tail` holding the tail of the list.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] These variables are read-only, and are semantically very similar to variable bindings established using the `let` operator in Lisp and Scheme.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Pattern matching also happens in local variable declarations.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] In this case, the return value of the call to `tail.partition` is a tuple — in this case, two lists.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] (Tuples differ from other types of containers, e.g. lists, in that they are always of fixed size and the elements can be of differing types — although here they are both the same.) Pattern matching is the easiest way of fetching the two parts of the tuple.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] The form `_ < pivot` is a declaration of an anonymous function with a placeholder variable; see the section above on anonymous functions.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] The list operators `::` (which adds an element onto the beginning of a list, similar to `cons` in Lisp and Scheme) and `:::` (which appends two lists together, similar to `append` in Lisp and Scheme) both appear.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Despite appearances, there is nothing "built-in" about either of these operators.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] As specified above, any string of symbols can serve as function name, and a method applied to an object can be written "infix"-style without the period or parentheses.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] In the pattern-matching example above, the body of the `match` operator is a partial function, which consists of a series of `case` expressions, with the first matching expression prevailing, similar to the body of a switch statement.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Finally, a partial function can be used alone, and the result of calling it is equivalent to doing a `match` over it.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Here a read-only *variable* is declared whose type is a function from lists of integers to lists of integers, and bind it to a partial function.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala is a pure object-oriented language in the sense that every value is an object.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Data types and behaviors of objects are described by classes and traits.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Class abstractions are extended by subclassing and by a flexible mixin-based composition mechanism to avoid the problems of multiple inheritance.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Traits are Scala's replacement for Java's interfaces.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Interfaces in Java versions under 8 are highly restricted, able only to contain abstract function declarations.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] This has led to criticism that providing convenience methods in interfaces is awkward (the same methods must be reimplemented in every implementation), and extending a published interface in a backwards-compatible way is impossible.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Traits are similar to mixin classes in that they have nearly all the power of a regular abstract class, lacking only class parameters (Scala's equivalent to Java's constructor parameters), since traits are always mixed in with a class.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] The `super` operator behaves specially in traits, allowing traits to be chained using composition in addition to inheritance.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] In other words, the call to `draw` first executed the code in `TitleDecoration` (the last trait mixed in), then (through the `super()` calls) threaded back through the other mixed-in traits and eventually to the code in `Window`, *even though none of the traits inherited from one another*.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] This is similar to the decorator pattern, but is more concise and less error-prone, as it doesn't require explicitly encapsulating the parent window, explicitly forwarding functions whose implementation isn't changed, or relying on run-time initialization of entity relationships.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] In other languages, a similar effect could be achieved at compile-time with a long linear chain of implementation inheritance, but with the disadvantage compared to Scala that one linear inheritance chain would have to be declared for each possible combination of the mix-ins.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala is equipped with an expressive static type system that mostly enforces the safe and coherent use of abstractions.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] This makes most static type declarations optional.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Static types need not be explicitly declared unless a compiler error indicates the need.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] In practice, some static type declarations are included for the sake of code clarity.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] A common technique in Scala, known as "enrich my library" (originally termed "pimp my library" by Martin Odersky in 2006; concerns were raised about this phrasing due to its negative connotations and immaturity), allows new methods to be used as if they were added to existing types.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] This is similar to the C# concept of extension methods but more powerful, because the technique is not limited to adding methods and can, for instance, be used to implement new interfaces.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] In Scala, this technique involves declaring an implicit conversion from the type "receiving" the method to a new type (typically, a class) that wraps the original type and provides the additional method.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] If a method cannot be found for a given type, the compiler automatically searches for any applicable implicit conversions to types that provide the method in question.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] This technique allows new methods to be added to an existing class using an add-on library such that only code that *imports* the add-on library gets the new functionality, and all other code is unaffected.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Importing the members of `MyExtensions` brings the implicit conversion to extension class `IntPredicates` into scope.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala's standard library includes support for futures and promises, in addition to the standard Java concurrency APIs.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Originally, it also included support for the actor model, which is now available as a separate source-available platform Akka licensed by Lightbend Inc.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Akka actors may be distributed or combined with software transactional memory (*transactors*).
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Alternative communicating sequential processes (CSP) implementations for channel-based message passing are Communicating Scala Objects, or simply via JCSP.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] An Actor is like a thread instance with a mailbox.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] It can be created by `system.actorOf`, overriding the `receive` method to receive messages and using the `!` (exclamation point) method to send a message.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] The following example shows an EchoServer that can receive messages and then print them.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala also comes with built-in support for data-parallel programming in the form of Parallel Collections integrated into its Standard Library since version 2.9.0.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] The following example shows how to use Parallel Collections to improve performance.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Besides futures and promises, actor support, and data parallelism, Scala also supports asynchronous programming with software transactional memory, and event streams.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] The most well-known open-source cluster-computing solution written in Scala is Apache Spark.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] Additionally, Apache Kafka, the publish–subscribe message queue popular with Spark and other stream processing technologies, is written in Scala.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] There are several ways to test code in Scala.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] ScalaTest supports multiple testing styles and can integrate with Java-based testing frameworks.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] ScalaCheck is a library similar to Haskell's QuickCheck. specs2 is a library for writing executable software specifications.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] ScalaMock provides support for testing high-order and curried functions.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p01] JUnit and TestNG are popular testing frameworks written in Java.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p02] Scala is often compared with Groovy and Clojure, two other programming languages also using the JVM.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p02] Substantial differences between these languages exist in the type system, in the extent to which each language supports object-oriented and functional programming, and in the similarity of their syntax to that of Java.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p02] Scala is statically typed, while both Groovy and Clojure are dynamically typed.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p02] This makes the type system more complex and difficult to understand but allows almost all type errors to be caught at compile-time and can result in significantly faster execution.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p02] By contrast, dynamic typing requires more testing to ensure program correctness, and thus is generally slower, to allow greater programming flexibility and simplicity.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p02] Regarding speed differences, current versions of Groovy and Clojure allow optional type annotations to help programs avoid the overhead of dynamic typing in cases where types are practically static.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p02] This overhead is further reduced when using recent versions of the JVM, which has been enhanced with an *invoke dynamic* instruction for methods that are defined with dynamically typed arguments.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p02] These advances reduce the speed gap between static and dynamic typing, although a statically typed language, like Scala, is still the preferred choice when execution efficiency is very important.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p02] Regarding programming paradigms, Scala inherits the object-oriented model of Java and extends it in various ways.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p02] Groovy, while also strongly object-oriented, is more focused in reducing verbosity.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p02] In Clojure, object-oriented programming is deemphasised with functional programming being the main strength of the language.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p02] Scala also has many functional programming facilities, including features found in advanced functional languages like Haskell, and tries to be agnostic between the two paradigms, letting the developer choose between the two paradigms or, more frequently, some combination thereof.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p02] Regarding syntax similarity with Java, Scala inherits much of Java's syntax, as is the case with Groovy.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p02] Clojure on the other hand follows the Lisp syntax, which is different in both appearance and philosophy.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p02] Back in 2013, when Scala was in version 2.10, the ThoughtWorks Technology Radar, which is an opinion based biannual report of a group of senior technologists, recommended Scala adoption in its languages and frameworks category.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p02] In the 2018 edition of the *State of Java* survey, which collected data from 5160 developers on various Java-related topics, Scala places third in terms of use of alternative languages on the JVM.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p02] Relative to the prior year's edition of the survey, Scala's use among alternative JVM languages fell from 28.4% to 21.5%, overtaken by Kotlin, which rose from 11.4% in 2017 to 28.8% in 2018.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p02] The Popularity of Programming Language Index, which tracks searches for language tutorials, ranked Scala 15th in April 2018 with a small downward trend, and 17th in Jan 2021.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p02] This makes Scala the 3rd most popular JVM-based language after Java and Kotlin, ranked 12th.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p02] The RedMonk Programming Language Rankings, which establishes rankings based on the number of GitHub projects and questions asked on Stack Overflow, in January 2021 ranked Scala 14th.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p02] Here, Scala was placed inside a second-tier group of languages–ahead of Go, PowerShell, and Haskell, and behind Swift, Objective-C, TypeScript, and R.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p02] The TIOBE index of programming language popularity employs internet search engine rankings and similar publication counting to determine language popularity.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p02] In September 2021, it showed Scala in 31st place.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p02] In this ranking, Scala was ahead of Haskell (38th) and Erlang, but below Go (14th), Swift (15th), and Perl (19th).
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p02] As of 2022, JVM-based languages such as Clojure, Groovy, and Scala are highly ranked, but still significantly less popular than the original Java language, which is usually ranked in the top three places.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p02] In November 2011, Yammer moved away from Scala for reasons that included the learning curve for new team members and incompatibility from one version of the Scala compiler to the next.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p02] In March 2015, former VP of the Platform Engineering group at Twitter Raffi Krikorian, stated that he would not have chosen Scala in 2011 due to its learning curve.
[src:play-framework/scala-programming-language-p02] The same month, LinkedIn SVP Kevin Scott stated their decision to "minimize [their] dependence on Scala".
